    <h2>History and context</h2>
    <div class="resource-history">
      <div class="resource-history-copy">
        <p>
          <b>Figure drawing</b> has a rich history that dates back to ancient times, with roots in the art of the Greeks and Romans. It became formalized in the Renaissance, where artists like Leonardo da Vinci and Michelangelo used figure drawing to study the human body and perfect their craft. In art schools, figure drawing remains a foundational practice, helping artists understand anatomy, proportion, and the subtleties of the human form.
        </p>
        <p>
          The primary <b>purpose</b> of figure drawing is to capture the essence and movement of the human body. At Figure It Out it’s also a low-stakes and friendly environment to practice drawing. These are for rough drawings, not final pieces of artwork. It’s a practice that helps artists explore the beauty of human anatomy, gestures, and emotions. Beyond technical skill, figure drawing sessions are a celebration of the human body in all its diversity and uniqueness.
        </p>
        <p>
          Figure drawing has a rich <b>intersection with queer history</b>. Notable queer artists like David Hockney, Paul Cadmus, and Catherine Opie have used figure drawing and live models to explore themes of identity, sexuality, and intimacy. By modeling, you are participating in a tradition that celebrates self-expression and inclusivity. Remember, you are beautiful, and this can be a wonderful act of self-empowerment. It’s not just about creating art—it's about being part of a community that honors and uplifts the human form in all its diversity. You are amazing for doing this, and you’re going to bring so much energy and creativity to the session!
        </p>
      </div>
